{{User:Xythecle/CRTBlock|title=Description|body=
[[File:Ent66A.png|350px|center|link=]]


The Hollows present as humanoid outlines composed entirely of coloured light. They have no filled interior. They are edges — the shape of a person with nothing inside the shape. When you stand in front of one you can see through it clearly. The background is not obscured. It is only contextualised strangely by the fact of the Hollow's presence.


They are two-dimensional entities existing within three-dimensional space. They present a face regardless of the observer's angle. There is no back to a Hollow. There is only and always the front, regardless of where you are standing.


The Hollow's height averages approximately 5'9", though individual specimens deviate. Their proportions are wrong. The limbs are elongated. The joints misaligned. The stance is haunted by an original that is no longer present.
Colouration varies. Red, yellow, orange, and white have all been documented, with white the most common. Each Hollow emits a faint ambient glow. The illumination is not helpful. It is the light of a monitor left running in an empty room — the light that makes visible the things wanderers did not want to see clearly.


Hollows are encountered most frequently in pairs or clusters of two or three. A solitary Hollow is rare, and every Wanderer who has reported a lone Hollow encounter has described it as markedly more distressing than any group sighting. Several Wanderers have attempted to describe why and landed, eventually, on the word lonely, and then immediately retracted it, as if the word felt too generous.
The research staff in AVEN has not retracted it.|body2=}}</div></div>
</div></span>
<div class="mw-collapsible mw-collapsed" id="mw-customcollapsible-2a">


<span class="mw-customtoggle-3a mw-customtoggle-3b"><div class="mw-collapsible t-audio-toggle-2" id="mw-customcollapsible-3b">
<div id="3"><div class="intro delay-1">
{{User:Xythecle/CRTBlock|title=Behaviour|body=
[[File:Ent66B.jpeg|350px|center|link=]]


The Hollows don't move. Not in any way that a person can catch, anyway. They stand frozen—always in the same spot, perfectly motionless, and they keep it up for as long as someone's watching. In fact, over four hundred sixty documented encounters, nobody has seen a Hollow close any gap. Not once. 


But here's the trouble—wanderers, those who track these things, often realize they're closer to a Hollow than they meant to be. They can't say how they moved, or when it happened. The approach was not evident at all, a new reality. And the moment of getting closer vanishes from memory just like that. To the person caught in it, the lost time just feels like a simple lapse in focus, not like they spent real minutes moving toward danger.


For a long time, the members of AVEN, the authority on such things, figured the Hollows' stillness was just part of what they were. That they were more like background threats, dangerous by being there rather than by doing anything. That explanation hung around for quite a while. 


None of that holds up now. The thinking's changed. AVEN's revised understanding admits that the stillness isn't because they can't move or because they're harmless. It's because they have no reason to act. Go through the encounter reports and rhe rhythm gets clearer: a Wanderer sees a Hollow. It stands there, unmoving. Then, something happens inside the observer—maybe it's curiosity, or it feels like recognition, or even a kind of deep, unexplained grief. And before long, the Wanderer steps closer. Not the Hollow. Never the Hollow.


So, it turns out, that stillness isn't about being passive. It's about waiting. The patience of the Hollows is what pulls people in.|body2=}}</div></div>
</div></span>
<div class="mw-collapsible mw-collapsed" id="mw-customcollapsible-3a">


<span class="mw-customtoggle-4a mw-customtoggle-4b"><div class="mw-collapsible t-audio-toggle-2" id="mw-customcollapsible-4b">
<div id="4"><div class="intro delay-1">
{{User:Xythecle/CRTBlock|title=The Episodes|body=
[[File:Ent66C.jpeg|250px|center|link=]]


On occasion, without warning and without apparent trigger, a Hollow will alter its outline.


For a span of seconds, its silhouette will reshape into something recognisable. A family member. A friend not thought of in years. Someone whose shape carries, even reduced to a pure outline of light, the specific weight of love, or grief, or something that has not been resolved and was not expected to surface here.
Equally, the shift may produce something else. Not a person the Wanderer loves. A shape from the bad hours. A figure assembled in the dark that the Wanderer hoped would stay there.


The episodes last only seconds. Witnesses describe them as feeling longer than they actually are. The return to the Hollow's neutral form brings no relief. This is one of the most consistent details across all documented accounts.


An internal station note, date withheld: three separate Wanderers, interviewed in the same week, described the shifted silhouette as depicting the same individual. They were not known to each other. They had not communicated. Cross-referencing is ongoing.|body2=}}</div></div>
</div></span>
<div class="mw-collapsible mw-collapsed" id="mw-customcollapsible-4a">


<span class="mw-customtoggle-5a mw-customtoggle-5b"><div class="mw-collapsible t-audio-toggle-2" id="mw-customcollapsible-5b">
<div id="5"><div class="intro delay-1">
{{User:Xythecle/CRTBlock|title=Cognitive Hazard and Exposure Effects|body=
The Hollows generate a kind of environmental cognitive hazard that's not easy to pin down. It doesn't pass from person to person through sound, sight, touch—none of that. The effect spreads out from the thing itself, almost like a field, or maybe radiation, if one is looking for an imperfect comparison. A wanderer simply being around it starts the clock.


The harm unfolds in stages, and after a certain point, there's no coming back. At first, a wanderer would notice they can't quite focus. Thoughts start to slip, one after another. There's a nagging sense that something, or someone, is watching them—but it's coming from somewhere inside, almost like there's a presence in their head. Wanderers describe it as feeling observed from within their own skulls. It's not paranoia, not exactly. It's more like inner surveillance.


Stick around longer, and things get weirder. Wanderers start losing short-term memories but, at the same time, old memories force their way back. Not the memories they want, these are the ones they thought they buried for good, the ones people are not ready to handle, especially not here, stripped of all context or comfort. And as these old ghosts return, their distress grows.


If wanderers keep pushing exposure, things get much worse. People slip into a vegetative state, no reaction to anything, can't move, not showing any sign they're conscious at all. They're still alive, technically, but that's all.


There's a brief window—just four to six hours after the vegetative state sets in—when it's still possible to reverse the damage. Get them away from the source and keep them actively engaged with conversation, touch, anything to anchor them to the world and they might come back. Miss that window, and it's over. The condition becomes permanent. Unless someone intervenes, death follows—not quickly, but inevitably from dehydration and starvation.


And yet, some people are kept alive in this state. Is that hope? Or something else? Depends who you ask. Usually, it shifts with the person's time at the station, and what they've seen the Hollows take.
|body2= '''[Stygians Annotation]'''

I have spent eleven months trying to determine what the Hollows are doing when they do this. Whether they are feeding. Whether the degradation is intended or incidental — a byproduct of proximity to something that was simply not built for human beings to stand near.


The number that troubles me most is not the number who reached full vegetative state. It is the number who described the initial exposure and used the word peaceful. Not distressing. Not frightening. Peaceful. 


As if something had been taken from them and the taking felt, at first, like relief.
}}</div></div>
</div></span>
<div class="mw-collapsible mw-collapsed" id="mw-customcollapsible-5a">


<span class="mw-customtoggle-6a mw-customtoggle-6b"><div class="mw-collapsible t-audio-toggle-2" id="mw-customcollapsible-6b">
<div id="6"><div class="intro delay-1">
{{User:Xythecle/CRTBlock|title=Post Mortem Progression|body=
The body undergoes no discernible biological decay for a period of days. Over the course of the first day or two, it becomes less substantial. Less defined. Less present. The internal structures disappear first. The outline remains after the interior has gone. Colour drains. A faint pulsating luminescence takes its place around the edges — a glow the research staff recognised, the first time they documented it, with the particular quiet of recognition rather than surprise.
The glow is the same glow emitted by every Hollow in Level 460.


In the final stage, the body rises. It suspends itself at whatever height it has reached. It remains there, motionless and inert.


It is a Hollow now.


Whether the Hollow population is self-replenishing from the deaths of those who encountered them, or whether this means the Hollows have always been this, or whether what the Hollows are is simply the remainder of everyone who has ever died in Level 460, held in outline, still here, still watching... [[User:Egglord|only god knows]].
|body2= '''[Stygians Annotation]'''

We keep not saying it. I will say it. The Hollows are what is left when everything else is taken. If Particle:Nothing absorbs consciousness over time — and the evidence that it does is substantial — then the Hollows are not predators in any conventional sense. They are the level's original inhabitants, or what those inhabitants became, or what every person who has ever died here has become.


The buildings feel aware because they are built from the substance that ate the people who once lived in them. The Hollows are that consumption made visible. They are not hunting.


They are waiting for the rest of us to join them.


And Level 460, being made of what it is made of, is infinitely patient.
}}</div></div>
</div></span>
<div class="mw-collapsible mw-collapsed" id="mw-customcollapsible-6a">
<div class="intro delay-1">
{{User:Xythecle/CRTBlock|title=The Classified Log|body=
I want to start by saying I knew about the Hollows before I entered the level. 


I had read the documentation. I knew what they were. I knew the thing about not approaching. I knew the thing about the distance closing without you noticing. I want to be clear that I knew all of this before I went in, because I think it matters that knowing did not help.


The level looks the way the documentation says it looks. The wireframe buildings. The flat ground that goes on wrong. The quality of the light, which is like a game rendered on hardware that was already obsolete when the game was made. I had been in for what felt like a few hours when I first saw one.


White-outlined. Standing near the base of one of the structures. 


Tall but wrong about the height somehow, the way the documentation says — like whoever assembled it had the instructions for a a person but had never actually seen one and was working from a description alone.



I stopped walking.


I told myself to stop walking and I stopped.


I looked at it from where I was and I did not move toward it and I was clear of it. I know I did not move toward it.


At some point the distance between us was smaller than it had been.


I noticed this the way you notice that the room has gotten darker while you were reading — not as an event but as a state that has already arrived. I was closer. 


I could see the individual edges of its outline with a clarity I had not had before. Through its centre I could see the wireframe of a building behind it, the two geometries occupying the same space without interfering with each other.


Then it shifted.


The outline changed. It took a shape I recognised. What I will say is that the shape was someone I had not let myself think about in a long time, and the grief that came with seeing that outline — even as an outline, even made of light at the edges of something that has no interior was specific.


It was accurate.


It had the exact weight of the real thing, which is not something I can explain and which I have been trying to explain to myself since I got here.


It lasted a few seconds.


Then it was just the Hollow again. The edges. The wrong arms. That same everlasting glowing pulse.


There was no relief when the shape went back.


I had expected there to be. 


I had thought that the return to the neutral form would release something, the way waking from a nightmare releases something, but there was nothing. 


The Hollow was just a Hollow and the grief was still the same weight and the distance between us was still smaller than I could account for.


The thing I keep returning to, in the hours when I am supposed to be sleeping, is the question of whether the Hollow showed me that shape because it found it in me or because it reached into wherever that grief was being kept and pulled it out and held it up, or whether the shape was something the Hollow already was, something it had been carrying, and the recognition I felt was not a projection but a meeting.


I know which answer the documentation supports.


<div style="margin-bottom: 500px;">I am not sure I believe the documentation Stygian wrote.</div>


